Nov 2 2009 	Knee Deep in the Hoopla	The Donatello is located in a great part of San Francisco, very close to Union Square, the cable cars, and China Town. A great deal of energy flows through this area, as well as the accompanying noise. So think of yourself as being part of a daily performance art exhibit including laughing, yelling people, honks, bus brakes and bums. It's quieter during the work week but spikes on the weekends.For the most part, it was invigorating. However, when you want to 'turn it off', the huge single-pane windows can only hold back so much - although they do partially compensate by opening a crack to let in the brisk air. It can be especially rancorous when the beer bottles start to fly or your neighbor uses the powerful plumbing (Mgmt: try looking into some hammer arresters).If you can deal with the hubbub, you will be treated with a nicely sized room with all of the necessities but not much in the way of trendy furniture (or calming color choices - unless you are a Bears or Gators fan). Beds are just to my liking - not too hard and not too soft. Yes, there is an icebox, safe, and wet bar.As you will typically find in this great city, service is great and friendly. Getting to your room is always a snap w/ two quick elevators and short hallways.For the money, you probably can't beat it, but it's not for the overly picky or sensitive tourist set that shouldn't be despoiling the city anyways. If you are traveling from the Fatherland w/ Bosha and can't figure out that a cable car is not your personal taxi: please stick to South Beach - they're waiting for you.	
