May 15 2009 	Excellent location great value and very friendly staff	We stayed here at the end of a two week holiday in California to enjoy the sites and sounds of San Francisco. Located just minutes from Union Square the location is excellent. Value for money also very good, with very competative rates for the area. Good links with local transport, a BART just down the road at Powell, and buses and cable cars to other interesting parts of the city, including Fishermans Wharf and Ocean Bay. Room is equipped with microwave, fridge, sink, cutlery and crockery, and coffee maker. Excellent free wifi for internet access and large telly with lots of channels, although our son wanted to watch the Stanley cup (ice hockey) on a channel that was not available....Only one minor gripe, our booking included continental breakfast, and on one day there was nothing left when we arrived. The continental breakfast just consists of coffee tea in thermos, orange juice (very nice) and muffin. Some days there were some croissants which made a nice change. Also fruit, apples, oranges, and bananas. Not much room to sit down to eat, so we normally took what was available back to the room to eat.Despite being in the middle of the city, our room on the 10th floor was very quiet. We were not disturbed by traffic noise at all.	
May 11 2009 	Excellent bang for the buck	Rubbing shoulders with some of the expensive hotels around Union Square, the prime location at a very good price is the best reason for staying at the Donatello. The room was spacious, well appointed and fairly attractive. It was also spotless, being kept in good order by very friendly room staff. The bed was good, but not the best. I thought too much street noise filtered through the windows during the night from street cleaners and various garbage trucks which always seemed to be around. Noise from adjacent rooms, however, was no worse than other hotels. The newspaper outside your door each morning was nice, but the complementary &quot;breakfast&quot; was less appealing. While the orange juice was fresh and coffee pretty good (both in paper cups), the high-fat, high-sugar pastries on offer were definitely not my idea of a nutritious breakfast. But at least they were fresh, gave you lots of energy... and who am I to look a gift horse in the mouth? Quibbles aside, I think the Donatello Hotel offers a great combination of amenities and location for the price (I paid less than $100 USD per night before taxes), and I would not hesitate to stay there again.	
May 11 2009 	Great Service Good Rooms Good Location. Breakfast?	This was the last leg of a 2 week vacation, a three night say in early May. This was our first time in SF, so I cannot compare to other places.The room (King, standard) was of sufficient size (400 sf) which I hear is a rarity in the city. The location is downtown amid the tall buildings. It is very close to Union Square and all methods of public transit.I chose the deal that included parking. I highly recommend this unless you are familiar with SF and know &quot;where&quot; to park already. Otherwise, Donatello is part of a property network that offers comps if you to listen to their sales pitch for an hour. Parking was one of the comps. We didn't do it, since I had parking in the deal already.In a city of this size, night time noise is expected and SF does not disappoint. We were 10th floor though I'm sure we could have been 1000th floor and it wouldn't have mattered. No biggie for me, I hope I didn't disturb the street life with my snoring.The city is busy and safety was of no real concern until dusk and later. When the throngs of people with permanent residences thin out, things looked a little tough a couple of times. There are some begging homeless, but I found them no more of a nuisance than the people that hand out girl cards in Las Vegas. Don't make eye contact and keep moving. In their defense, I saw a number of them giving directions. This is a characteristic of the city - not the hotel. I did not see anyone &quot;living&quot; near the hotel at night.You want service? You got it! We were immediately checked in and dished off to the concierge for a warm welcome and some useful information. Special mention of Ed (It's always Monday at the Donatello) at the desk, Sarah the concierge, and Joe the bellman. I'm sorry I don't remember the valet, but top notch there, too. Sarah was spot on with restaurant recommendations two out of three times (Fino's downtown and Alioto's on the wharf). Even the third was good - just not &quot;San Francisco&quot; good.The room also included a complimentary continental breakfast, available from 7:00 to 9:30. We were 0-2 on finding anything other than a muffin or a banana / apple. This was a bit of a disappointment (which I have also seen in other reviews). Sheesh, get a big fridge, have some cereals, pastries, jams, jellies, fruits, bagels, cream cheese - you know, the standards - and have enough to last the entire 2 1/2 hours. A little more attention to this and there will be precious little negative to say about the Donatello.I'm glad I stayed and look forward to a return visit.	
May 10 2009 	Solid value near Union Square	This was our first overnight stay in San Francisco, so although we have been there before on day trips, I have no other hotel experiences in SF to compare it to. That being said, we travel frequently as a family so I am familiar with similar such options in general.The valet parking package for an extra $20 a day is simply unbeatable in THIS city and there were no issues in that regard. I found other places charging $30-$50+ per night, so as &quot;locals&quot; making the trip from Monterey, we really had no options other than bring the car and were pleasantly surprised with it. The room itself was fairly spacious, but the layout a bit inefficient. This may have been due to being next to the elevator, but for the amount of space, separate living and sleeping areas would have been nice. The sofabed was located in the same room as the bed, so no luck in being able to put the kids to sleep at a different time. The furnishings are in a modern blue and tan decor, and the tv was nice so we still enjoyed the room and found it a pretty good value. Free wireless internet was also included and worked without issue. A small fridge and microwave were also included.We stayed on the sixth floor on a Friday -Sunday on Mother's Day weekend and found outside/street noise to be very prevalent at night with Saturday noise levels being enough to disturb sleep repeatedly. This may be common for hotels at Union Square as there are several night clubs in the area. I don't blame the hotel for this, but may be a consideration for travelers. Within hotel noise was not really an issue, even by the elevator, with only a rare loud grouping passing by. Other than the night noise, everything about this hotel was pleasant. Staff was friendly and attentive, the property clean, and the value for the space is outstanding. I would definitely come back if it was just my wife and myself, but might look for the quieter financial district when bringing children or perhaps insist on a higher floor to see if that alleviates the issue.Finally, a few notes about the trip itself to help others.First, skip the cable cars. Yes, I know that they sound like a romantic experience but the reality is long lines and packed cars, so you are far more likely to be viewing another rider's behind than parts of the city. For the same price ($5 a person) you can get a limo from Union Square to Fisherman's Wharf. If you absolutely must get on one, you will likely need to get on at either end of the line as we saw people repeatedly be told no room at each stop.Second, go to touristy spots early. We went to Pier 39 at opening (10 AM) and without the crowds, is actually a great place for sightseeing and to take the kids. By 1-3, the crowds are there and expect waits for a lot of stuff. Same goes for the Exploratorium. We got there at 10 on a free day expecting the worst, and again, not too bad for the first hour or two. Then the crowds commence. From a practical standpoint, we found 2-3 hours sufficient to view each.We also did the 1 hour Bay Cruise and found that enjoyable. Bring your jacket though.All in all, a very nice stay-cation and well worth the weekend. Thanks SF!	
