Feb 25 2009 	Good Value for the money but Noisy !	I was there overthe Valentines long weekend, and asked in advance for a quiet room with a view. I got a room on the 5th floor with a little terrace, but in Feb it was of no use. It was too close to street level (the noise was too much), and I didn't have a very good sleep that night. When I walked into the room I found it to be tiny, and the carpet and bathroom a bit tired. I asked at the front desk if I could get another room, and the the girl left a note for the day staff to set me up with a *better* room (she claimed there would be none available until the next morning) . The next morning I headed downstairs and talked to Jesus (yes that's his name) and he was very nice, and relocated me and my bags (while I was out) to the 10th floor. The room there was mich nicer, however the noise was still problematic, but not as bad. There was some kind of shrill that kept coming from across the street, and it occurred to me on my last night that it's the doorman (I think) of the hotel across the street, using a whistle to hail cabs. It was rather annoying, but if you kept all the windows closed I managed to get some sleep. The cleaning staff kept opening the windows every day, so I had to keep closing them.Oh yeah...the maids knock on your door at 8:00 a.m. !!! which is incredibly stoopid...so you need to leave the &quot;Do Not Disturb&quot; sign out, or expect to be waken up, and they will come in unless you go to the door to tell them to go away !The shower-head was a disaster. You cannot adjust the pressure, and instead of a nice &quot;shower&quot;, it bolted out like a firehose, and I literally had to get on my hands and knees in the tub to keep my scalp from blowing off from the water pressure (it was the same type of shower-head in both rooms I was in, so I suspect it's the same all over the hotel). It was also too low vertically. If you're 6 feet or taller, you'd have to be bending over regardless. Either way...you'll be on your hands and knees to shower, so good luck with that !The breakfast room on the &quot;Club Level&quot; (same floor as the gym) was nice enough, and the continental style food was fine. Good coffee, bagels and pastries ! There is only seating for about 10 people though, and the hotel has about 20 floors...so you do the math. After one attempt, I just took the food to go after that. Once I just went up to get it and came right back down to my room with a paper plate of food.The front desk staff and the doormen were great though, they were very accomodating in listening to concerns, and orfering airport shuttles. They also have a map pad that is handy for when you're heading out at the strart of your day. I got a new sheet every day, and never managed to get lost !The beds are hard to describe, but they are very comfortable, and linens were good.The rooms have FREE Wi-Fi, so I was happy about that. I could check my email and FaceBook every night without getting gouged with extra fees !The price I paid was based on a &quot;recession special&quot; and for San Fran it was pretty good ($620. for 5 nights), so there is value for the money ~ I was happy once I got the 2nd room, otherwise my stay there would of been a negative one I think.It's at a good downtown location, just a block from Union Square, and a couple from Market St. (major shopping). You need transportation down to the wharf (waterfront) area, but that's Ok. I pre-bought a 2 day &quot;On/Off&quot; double-decker tour bus ticket, and it's main stop is at Union Square, so my transporation around town was taken care of, and I got the narration as I went ! All the &quot;On/Off&quot; tour bus companies stop at Union Square, so all good there - I hightly recommed them !..they only stop at the major tourist stops/areas all over town (including both sides of the Golden Gate Bridge), and you get a narration as you go...I only took cabs at night after the tour bus's stopped (after 5 p.m.). They service each stop every 30 minutes or so (although there was one cheap company I read about that only did it once an hour - so shop accordingly !Anyway, I digress. The Donatello would likely get my business again, but keep in mind the above, and the fact that the actual rooms do not look as nice as their website. But San Francisco is an expensive town for accomodation, and their rates are competitive, so unless you're made of cash, it's a good option to keep in mind.	
Feb 25 2009 	Great in many ways but not perfect	We just returned from a 2 day stay at the Donatello. The location is great for a city visit. The rooms were immaculate, the staff was friendly and helpful (with one exception). Our room had a plumbing problem and the maintenance staff was up to fix it, even before I returned from the front desk. Even though the literature promised wireless internet in the rooms, none was available in ours. There was a lot of noise in the room. Some from the water pipes and other from some sort of loud machinery that was run somewhere in the hotel. The staff were great and went out of their way to be helpful. The one exception was a woman who saw her job, at the club room, as a rather grim customs inspector, making sure we all signed in and that my wife not steal the 4 grapes that she was bringing to her daughter, who was not feeling well. The bottom line is, I would definitely stay there again. The charm and service outweighs the few draw backs.	
