Nov 11 2008 	Great Experience	The Donatello is a true San Francisco gem, tucked away only one block from Union Square. The property itself is staffed by friendly, knowledgable staff. They welcome your questions and are there to make your stay enjoyable. When booking, I suggest you request a high floor to negate at least part of the street noise. Our room was spacious, especially by the San Francisco standard. It had a small refrigerator which proved quite useful. The flat screen television and DVD player were both nice touches.The carpet showed no signs of stains while the furniture did show a few nicks and minimal guest trauma. The bed linens were of moderate, hotel quality. The bed itself was fairly comfortable. The robes provided were quite plush and of very good quality.The hotel offers nightly turn down service which was very nice. If you would like to opt out of it simply place the &quot;do not disturb sign&quot; on your door. If you want ice you will have to call the Bell Captain for complimentary delivery, no ice machines here. Both times we requested ice it was delivered within five minutes.Housekeeping was prompt and did an excellent job. No surprises upon our return to the room.Room service is limited. The only food items offered are from Zingari Restaurant which is on site. (**I do not recommend this restaraunt** please check the reviews before going)The concierge can recommend a restaraunt if you're not familiar with the area. They are very apprachable at the Donatello, not &quot;snooty&quot; in the least.At fourteen stories in height, don't expect a stellar city scape view though. We were in the midst of surrounding buildings, all seemed to be taller than ours.The Club level is on the fifteenth floor which will offer you some great views of the area. It has a comfortable feel to it, including a fireplace and offering self-service coffee and teas. You will also fing a hotel concierge there in addition to the concierge located in the lobby. If you're looking for an intimate, service oriented, upscale but unpretentious property in San Francisco. I would have to say that you won't be dissapointed here, I know we weren't.	
Nov 11 2008 	Pleasant place 	The Donatello is a medium-size hotel which is a just a few minutes walk from Union Square. We decided that wed probably prefer this area to Fishermans Wharf, and we were glad we made that choice.This is a well-run place. The rooms were nicely furnished, the bathroom was small-ish but adequate, and it was clean. Staff members all seemed very pleasant and efficient.A really big plus is that the Donatello provides free wi-fi access. After experiencing some rip-off charges elsewhere, we appreciated the gesture.The breakfast in the top floor Club Room is a great deal, but the room is too small to cope with demand and so its either balance your bagel on your lap or take it back to your room.There was a limited view of high-rise buildings from our room  as youd expect in the city centre. Also, there is a very popular night club just across the road, so there was some noise in the early hours as people were leaving. There are some other lively bars and a few nice restaurants in the area - although it is mainly a shopping location.The hotels piano bar is pleasant, and offers very reasonably-priced drinks.The Donatello proved a good value deal in the heart of the city.	
Nov 10 2008 	Nice Especially for the price!	We chose the Donatello as we were staying in San Francisco for a week-long trip to attend a wedding. We booked here after looking around the web for quite a while, trying to find a hotel room in the right price range and yet also big enough for our stay. My husband and I were traveling with our 9-month old baby and needed a room large enough to fit a crib off to the side. The Donatello fit the bill perfectly. It is not the most luxurious hotel room I have ever been in, and the bathroom was a bit on the duller side, but it is clean, large (ESPECIALLY for SF), and pretty well appointed. There was even a little foyer area where we could put the crib so that our baby could sleep in the quiet dark while we had some lights on in the room. It might not be what you're looking for in a honeymoon suite, but it's a perfect fit for a business trip, a nice little get-away on a budget or a family vacation. Our hotel room was NOTHING like what the previous user's was like, with mold and peeling paint. If it were, we would not have stayed. The crib DID seem a little old and I will warn you to BRING YOUR OWN CRIB SHEET! The crib sheet was so big and loose it was a potential suffocation hazard and we did marvel that the hotel was risking a lawsuit, not to mention a child accident. Fortunately, we had own own. We really appreciated the sideboard with the empty refrigerator and the sink. It helped a lot with being able to bring in food, keeping formula and the washing and rinsing of the baby bottles. The hotel staff was friendly and helpful and quite willing to put up with our check-in confusion. The maids did a terrific job everyday. One problem: The walls are somewhat thin. We could not hear other people for the most part, but my mother stayed in the room next to ours and, when the baby was having a particularly fussy night, my mother could hear her crying. Short of a screaming baby, however, not a lot of noise gets through. And, as we didn't receive any complaints, we're assuming it wasn't horrible for other guests. But to any other guests out there, we apologize if it were. Overall, this hotel did a good job of meeting our family's needs.	
Nov 7 2008 	A good choice	My husband and I recently returned from a week in California. We stayed 3 nights at The Donatello in San Francisco. We found the hotel to be a good choice for us. The room was extremely nice; large and well equipped. There was a wine and cheese party the afternoon we arrived (Friday) which is a once-a-week event. This took place on the top floor where the complimentary continental breakfast was offered every morning. Staff was very friendly and helpful, as other reviewers have noted. Housekeeping standards were high. The location, while convenient to Union Square, public transportation, etc., was sort of on the fringe, and you didn't want to wander too far or you'd be in a pretty seedy area.	
