Oct 14 2008 	Comfortable Modern and Well Located	Hotels near Union Square tend to fall into 2 categories: ultra posh and very expensive or less-expensive &quot;character&quot; buildings that have been nicely restored but are still old buildings with small rooms and no A/C . The Donatello is one of the few that doesn't fit into either category.The hotel is a 1960s-ish building with big rooms, fitness center and modern elevators. Rooms have king-size beds plus a queen sofa-bed, new (but not fancy) furniture, A/C and a big LCD TV and DVD player. A real bonus was the small kitchenette in our room with microwave, empty bar fridge (who drinks those minis anyway?), bar sink, and supplies including wine glasses, plates, cutlery, cutting board and corkscrew. Our room rate also included continental breakfast each morning.It is clean and the staff are super nice. We did have a few small problems: there was no bedding for the sofa bed even though our reservation clearly specified we were a party of 3; and the latches on the aluminum frame casement windows were so worn that the windows would not latch closed. Both of these problems were cheerfully corrected by the staff  they even sent someone up from the engineering department to show me how to work the DVD player.Like virtually all of San Francisco, noise is a problem if youre a light sleeper. Upon check-in we requested a room on the highest floor available (10th of 14) and the light sleepers in our group of 3 women slept with ear plugs.We had a pleasant and comfortable stay at this well-located hotel. I would certainly stay there again.	
